posts.subject: Has anyone noticed how frickin fast ZeroNet is today?
posts.body:
Could be the norm if more people would seed.


Yes, setting aside a machine to seed will cost you money. So what's an uncensorable source worth to you?

Those with programming instincts and skill should seriously consider leaving their mark on Zeronet. It would be incredibly useful if real newspapers could setup shop here at low or near zero cost. But newspapers need intuitive tools - and we just don't have them. Yet.

And if a million ZeroNet seeders could come into existence, there is just no way a centralized system could match ZeroNet's performance. 

There are fundamental problems with centralization which are mitigated ONLY by expensive efforts to provide local cache. That's what Akamai and other content delivery networks are all about.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akamai_Technologies

But when you own a thing - you control it. Content delivery is much safer in the hands of Zeronet citizens. Trust NO ONE.

In the fullness of time, such efforts also have a real chance of destroying what we now call the MSM. Mainstream media.

Think Conan level destruction:

"Crush your enemies, see them driven before you, and hear the lamentation of the women!"

posts.subject: Glenn Greenwald's resignation letter
posts.body: "I reasoned that as long as The Intercept remained a place where my own right of journalistic independence was not being infringed, I could live with all of its other flaws. posts.subject: Text threads
posts.body:
A little old lady went to Co-op to buy cat food. She picked up four cans and took them to the check-out counter.

The girl at the cash register said, "I'm sorry, but Jim says we cannot sell you cat food without proof that you have a cat. A lot of old people buy cat food to eat, and the management wants proof that you are buying the cat food for your cat."

The little old lady went home, picked up her cat and brought it back to the store. They sold her the cat food.

The next day, she tried to buy two cans of dog food. Again the cashier said "I'm sorry, but we cannot sell you dog food without proof that you have a dog. A lot of old people buy dog food to eat, but Jim wants proof that you are buying the dog food for your dog."

So she went home and brought in her dog. She then was able to buy the dog food.
The next day she brought in a box with a hole in the lid. The little old lady asked the cashier to stick her finger in the hole. The cashier said, "No, you might have a snake in there."

The little old lady assured her that there was nothing in the box that would harm her. So the cashier put her finger into the box and quickly pulled it out. She said to the little old lady, "That smells like shit."

The little old lady said, "Yes, it is. I want to buy three rolls of toilet paper."

Yeah, sites do piss on you...but there are workarounds. Can't imagine anyone using their ISP connection directly anyway. You should be using a VPN for casual use, switching to the Tor network when you don't even trust the VPN. So the only real gotcha I've ever seen over 2 decades are these damn video streamers. If you run a relay you MUST subscribe to a SmartProxy service. It's not expensive...but it's another thing you hafta fuck with. And some in your household may not appreciate being cut off when you aren't around to maintain it . Like when your IP addresses changes. Problem is real.

Tor does need more relays. An easy way to do it is to build an IPfire router. That will completely secure your DNS AND give you an up to date Tor relay. Takes about 70 days to become a trusted relay.
